---
/**
 * "Grover + Search reality" — v3 Phase 4 essay.
 *
 * Two halves:
 *   1. Algorithm (ALG-04): real simulator-backed amplitude amplification
 *      over 4 qubits = 16 candidates. Uniform superposition, phase
 *      oracle on the marked state, diffusion as inversion about the
 *      mean. AmplitudeBars shows signed amplitudes with the marked
 *      state going negative after the oracle, then concentrating
 *      after diffusion.
 *   2. Use-case reality (USE-03): SearchComparison plots classical
 *      `N/2` average probes against Grover's `⌊π/4·√N⌋`. The widget
 *      is formula-only beyond `N = 16` (the simulator cap).
 *
 * Locked sentence on RSA: "No — Grover does not break RSA. That is
 *   Shor; see the next essay." — keeps the next-essay handoff clean.
 *
 * Footer-nav at Phase 4 execution time: `teleportation → grover →
 *   sandbox`. If Phase 3 (`superdense-coding`) lands after this commit,
 *   that essay's commit will weave itself in front of grover and
 *   adjust the chain.
 */
import EssayLayout from "../layouts/EssayLayout.astro";
import MathBlock from "../components/MathBlock.astro";
import MathNerds from "../components/MathNerds.astro";
import CircuitView from "../components/CircuitView.astro";
import SandboxLink from "../components/SandboxLink.astro";
import AmplitudeBars from "../components/AmplitudeBars.astro";
import SearchComparison from "../components/SearchComparison.astro";
import {
  buildGroverCircuit,
  optimalGroverIterations,
  runGrover,
  type GroverSnapshot,
} from "../lib/quantum";

const QUBITS = 4;
const N = 1 << QUBITS;
const DEFAULT_MARKED = 0b1011; // |1011⟩ — a non-zero pattern, easy to spot
const K_OPT = optimalGroverIterations(N);

// Precompute a snapshot sequence per marked basis state so the widget
// can swap sequences client-side without importing the simulator. We
// give 3 extra iterations beyond optimal so the reader can overshoot
// and watch P(marked) drop again — the textbook over-rotation.
const snapshotsByMarked: Record<number, GroverSnapshot[]> = Object.fromEntries(
  Array.from({ length: N }, (_, marked) => [
    marked,
    runGrover({ qubits: QUBITS, markedIndex: marked, iterations: K_OPT + 3 }),
  ]),
);

// Compact 2-qubit Grover circuit (N=4, marked=|11⟩, one iteration).
// Same circuit object feeds CircuitView's "Copy as Qiskit" and the
// sandbox starter so the page and its mirror in sandbox-links.test.ts
// share one source of truth.
const demoCircuit = buildGroverCircuit(4, 3, 1);
---

<EssayLayout
  title="Grover + Search reality"
  subtitle="Amplitude amplification finds a marked needle in N candidates in roughly √N steps. Quadratic — not magic. The classical baseline is N/2 average probes; Grover bends that curve, but it does not flatten it."
  description="Watch a 4-qubit Grover search amplify a marked basis state through oracle phase flips and diffusion. Then compare iteration counts against classical linear scan from N=16 up to N=1024 — same algorithm family that gives a √N speedup against AES-256 brute force, and that does NOT break RSA."
>
  <p>
    Suppose you have a black-box function <code>f(x)</code> that
    returns <code>1</code> on exactly one input out of <code>N</code>
    and <code>0</code> on everything else. The only test available is
    to try an input and ask. A classical search has to keep guessing
    — on average it takes <code>N/2</code> calls, and worst case
    <code>N − 1</code>. A textbook example: brute-forcing a
    fixed-length password against a hash, where every guess costs one
    hash evaluation and the only signal is "match" or "no match".
  </p>

  <p>
    Grover's algorithm cuts that to roughly <code>√N</code> calls. For
    a 4-qubit register (<code>N = 16</code>) it takes
    <strong>3</strong> oracle calls and finds the answer with
    probability ≈ 0.96. That sounds magical, and the rest of this
    essay is the careful look that says: it isn't, and it doesn't do
    what the breathless press releases imply. There is no hidden
    "lookup table in superposition." There's a real linear algebra
    trick that nudges amplitudes around, and a real ceiling on what
    those amplitudes can do.
  </p>

  <h2>Uniform superposition</h2>

  <p>
    Start in the all-zero state and apply Hadamard to every qubit.
    The resulting state has every basis index with the same
    amplitude — <code>1/√N</code> — which is also why each
    measurement probability is <code>1/N</code>. The bar chart below
    shows the signed amplitudes (not probabilities); at iteration 0
    every bar is the same positive height.
  </p>

  <MathBlock tex="|s\rangle \;=\; H^{\otimes n} |0\rangle^{\otimes n} \;=\; \frac{1}{\sqrt{N}} \sum_{x=0}^{N-1} |x\rangle" />

  <h2>Oracle: a phase flip on the marked state</h2>

  <p>
    The oracle is a unitary <code>O<sub>f</sub></code> that maps
    <code>|x⟩ ↦ (−1)<sup>f(x)</sup>|x⟩</code>. For a single marked
    state <code>x*</code> this is the same as flipping the sign of
    one amplitude and leaving the rest alone. After one oracle call
    the marked bar drops below the zero axis; every other bar is
    unchanged.
  </p>

  <p>
    The simulator under this page does exactly that — a real sign
    flip on the marked amplitude, no fake animation, no new gate
    invented to make the visual prettier. Open the widget below,
    pick a marked state in the dropdown, and press <em>Next</em>
    once. Watch the marked bar swing negative while every other bar
    stays put.
  </p>

  <h2>Diffusion: inversion about the mean</h2>

  <p>
    On its own the oracle does nothing visible — squaring the
    amplitudes gives the same probabilities back, because
    <code>(−1/√N)² = 1/N</code>. The sign flip becomes useful only
    when the next operator pivots every amplitude around their
    mean: <code>a<sub>i</sub> ↦ 2 · mean(a) − a<sub>i</sub></code>.
    That's called the diffusion operator, sometimes the
    <strong>Grover operator</strong> <code>D = 2|s⟩⟨s| − I</code>.
    The geometric picture: reflect every amplitude across the
    average. The marked amplitude was sitting <em>well below</em>
    the average (it's the only negative one), so reflecting it
    sends it <em>well above</em> — the rest barely move.
  </p>

  <AmplitudeBars
    snapshotsByMarked={snapshotsByMarked}
    markedIndex={DEFAULT_MARKED}
    qubits={QUBITS}
    caption="4-qubit Grover (N = 16). Bars are signed amplitudes — positive above the axis, negative below. Marked state is highlighted. Press Next to apply oracle + diffusion; k_opt is the textbook optimal iteration count."
  />

  <p>
    Try this: from iteration 0, press <em>Next</em> three times.
    That's <code>k<sub>opt</sub> = ⌊π/4·√16⌋ = 3</code>, the
    textbook stopping point. The marked bar should be visibly the
    tallest, with probability around <code>0.96</code> in the
    aria-live readout. Press <em>Next</em> a few more times and
    watch the marked probability <em>drop</em> — Grover is a
    rotation in a 2D subspace, and you can over-rotate past the
    target. The optimal count is not "more is better"; it's a hard
    sweet spot.
  </p>

  <h2>The circuit, and Qiskit on real hardware</h2>

  <p>
    The simulator under the widget runs oracle and diffusion as
    direct state-vector operations — the cleanest possible reading
    of the algorithm at our 4-qubit cap. For the
    <em>circuit-level</em> story (gates on wires) we drop down to
    <code>N = 4</code> (2 qubits) where the oracle is just
    <code>CZ(q<sub>0</sub>, q<sub>1</sub>)</code> and the diffusion
    is <code>H<sup>⊗2</sup> · X<sup>⊗2</sup> · CZ · X<sup>⊗2</sup> · H<sup>⊗2</sup></code>.
    One iteration is enough — for <code>N = 4</code>, Grover finds
    the marked state with probability <em>exactly</em> 1.
  </p>

  <CircuitView
    circuit={demoCircuit}
    caption="A compact 2-qubit Grover circuit for marked = |11⟩. CZ is decomposed as H · CNOT · H on the target so the simulator's gate set covers it. The 'Copy as Qiskit' button gives you the same circuit ready to run on hardware."
  />

  <p class="my-6">
    <SandboxLink circuit={demoCircuit} label="Remix this Grover starter in the sandbox →" />
  </p>

  <p>
    The 4-qubit AmplitudeBars use direct state-vector
    oracle/diffusion because the in-browser simulator caps at 4
    qubits and a full multi-controlled oracle decomposition gets
    noisy fast. The Qiskit-export button is the path for running
    decomposed Grover on real hardware. Take the 2-qubit circuit,
    paste it into a notebook, and scale it up.
  </p>

  <h2>How big is the speedup, actually?</h2>

  <p>
    Classical unstructured search costs <code>N/2</code> on average,
    <code>N − 1</code> worst case. Grover costs
    <code>⌊π/4·√N⌋</code>. The widget below maps that side by side
    over sizes the reader can hold in their head:
  </p>

  <SearchComparison
    caption="Drag the slider through seven search-space sizes. Beyond N = 16 the numbers come from the formulas — the in-browser simulator is hard-capped at 4 qubits, so 'simulate 1024 candidates' would be a lie."
  />

  <p>
    <code>N = 16</code> goes from 8 average probes to 3 iterations,
    which is a real speedup but not a jaw-dropper. The gap widens
    as <code>N</code> grows: at <code>N = 1024</code> it's 512 vs
    25, more than 20× — and at AES-256 sizes
    (<code>N = 2<sup>256</sup></code>) the square-root drops the
    workload from 2<sup>256</sup> down to 2<sup>128</sup>. That
    last figure is the source of the "Grover halves the effective
    key length" rule of thumb in post-quantum cryptography: a
    Grover-armed adversary cuts your symmetric security exponent
    in half, so you double the key length to stay even.
  </p>

  <h2>What Grover does <em>not</em> do</h2>

  <p>
    The press-release version of Grover often sounds like
    "computer can check every database row at once," and that's
    misleading. Two clarifications:
  </p>

  <ul class="my-4 list-disc space-y-2 pl-6 text-ink">
    <li>
      <strong>You still pay for the oracle.</strong> The
      <code>√N</code> count is in oracle <em>calls</em> — but
      whatever your oracle does to compute <code>f(x)</code> still
      runs. If checking one candidate requires hashing a 16-byte
      input, Grover does <code>√N</code> hashes, not zero. The
      speedup is in the count of calls, not in the cost per call.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>It is not a database lookup.</strong> A real database
      has structure — indices, B-trees, hash maps — and classical
      lookup in <code>O(1)</code> or <code>O(log N)</code> already
      beats Grover. Grover wins only when the search space is
      genuinely unstructured: you have to ask the oracle, and the
      oracle is the only signal.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    The cleanest way to remember the line:
  </p>

  <div class="my-6 overflow-x-auto rounded-lg border border-line">
    <table class="w-full text-sm">
      <thead class="bg-surface-sunken/60">
        <tr>
          <th class="px-4 py-2 text-left font-medium text-ink-emphasis">Grover changes</th>
          <th class="px-4 py-2 text-left font-medium text-ink-emphasis">Grover does not change</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody class="divide-y divide-line">
        <tr>
          <td class="px-4 py-2 align-top">
            Oracle-call count: <code>N/2 → √N</code> (quadratic).
          </td>
          <td class="px-4 py-2 align-top">
            Per-call cost: whatever <code>f(x)</code> requires.
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="px-4 py-2 align-top">
            Symmetric-key brute-force exponent (halves it).
          </td>
          <td class="px-4 py-2 align-top">
            Sorted-index lookup; classical wins in <code>O(log N)</code>.
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="px-4 py-2 align-top">
            Practical upper bound for unstructured brute force.
          </td>
          <td class="px-4 py-2 align-top">
            Public-key factoring (RSA): that's <em>Shor</em>, not Grover.
          </td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <p>
    <strong>No — Grover does not break RSA. That is Shor; see the
    next essay.</strong> RSA's hard problem is integer factoring,
    not unstructured search. Shor's algorithm uses the quantum
    Fourier transform and period finding to give an
    <em>exponential</em> (not just quadratic) speedup on factoring;
    Grover gives you nothing on that problem. Doubling your RSA
    modulus does not save you from Shor the way doubling AES-256
    saves you from Grover. That's why post-quantum cryptography
    standards (lattice schemes, hash-based signatures, code-based
    KEMs) target the Shor threat, while AES-256 stays AES-256 with
    a halved effective security margin.
  </p>

  <h2>Self-test</h2>

  <ol class="my-6 list-decimal space-y-3 pl-6 text-ink">
    <li>
      In the AmplitudeBars widget, overshoot <code>k<sub>opt</sub></code>
      by typing a larger number into the iterations override. What
      happens to <code>P(marked)</code> at iteration 6? At
      iteration 8? Why is the curve not monotone? (Hint: Grover is
      a rotation by a fixed angle in the 2D subspace spanned by
      <code>|s⟩</code> and <code>|x*⟩</code>; you can rotate past
      the target.)
    </li>
    <li>
      AES-128 has a 128-bit key and brute-force complexity
      2<sup>128</sup>. A Grover-armed adversary spends roughly
      2<sup>64</sup> oracle calls. Why does NIST currently
      recommend AES-256 (effective 2<sup>128</sup> against Grover)
      for traffic that must remain secret 50 years from now? What
      changes if you're protecting <em>RSA-encrypted</em>
      ciphertext instead, where Shor — not Grover — is the threat?
    </li>
  </ol>

  <MathNerds title="The Grover operator as a rotation in a 2-D subspace">
    <p>
      Let <code>|x*⟩</code> be the marked basis state and
      <code>|u⟩</code> the equal superposition of the <em>other</em>
      <code>N − 1</code> states. Every state Grover ever produces
      lives in the 2D real subspace
      <code>span&#123;|u⟩, |x*⟩&#125;</code>. The starting uniform
      superposition <code>|s⟩</code> sits in that span:
    </p>
    <MathBlock tex="|s\rangle \;=\; \sin\theta\, |x^*\rangle + \cos\theta\, |u\rangle, \quad \sin\theta = \frac{1}{\sqrt{N}}" />
    <p>
      The oracle <code>O<sub>f</sub> = I − 2|x*⟩⟨x*|</code> is a
      reflection across <code>|u⟩</code>. The diffusion
      <code>D = 2|s⟩⟨s| − I</code> is a reflection across
      <code>|s⟩</code>. Two reflections in a plane compose to a
      rotation by <code>2θ</code>:
    </p>
    <MathBlock tex="(D\, O_f)^k\, |s\rangle \;=\; \sin\bigl((2k + 1)\theta\bigr) |x^*\rangle + \cos\bigl((2k+1)\theta\bigr) |u\rangle" />
    <p>
      Maximize <code>P(x*) = sin²((2k+1)θ)</code> by solving
      <code>(2k+1)θ ≈ π/2</code>, giving
      <code>k<sub>opt</sub> ≈ π/(4θ) − 1/2 ≈ (π/4)·√N</code> for
      small <code>θ</code>. That's the formula in the widget.
      Overshoot past <code>k<sub>opt</sub></code> and you rotate
      past <code>|x*⟩</code>; under-shoot and you stop short.
    </p>
    <p>
      In the simulator we run all <code>N</code> amplitudes
      explicitly — no exploiting the 2D structure — because at
      <code>N ≤ 16</code> there is no compute advantage in being
      clever, and the explicit amplitudes are what the
      AmplitudeBars chart paints. The 4-qubit cap is the same one
      the rest of the site enforces (REQ-13); Qiskit-export is
      the bridge for circuits that exceed it.
    </p>
  </MathNerds>

  <Fragment slot="footer-nav">
    <a href="/superdense-coding" class="hover:text-ink">← Superdense coding</a>
    <a href="/shor" class="hover:text-ink">Next: Shor + post-quantum →</a>
  </Fragment>
</EssayLayout>

<script>
  // No essay-specific JS — AmplitudeBars, SearchComparison,
  // CircuitView, and SandboxLink each ship their own hydrators.
</script>
